04782nam a22006255i 9780226307930DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152000ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263079307 a10.7208/97802263079302doi  a(DE-B1597)524237  a(OCoLC)1125191924  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aLC225.3b.C86 2000 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a371.19/2/09732211 aCutler, William W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aParents and Schools :bThe 150-Year Struggle for Control in American Education /cWilliam W. Cutler. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (298 p.) :b9 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. From Adversaries to Advocates -- tCHAPTER 2. Home Rule or Ruled at Home? -- tCHAPTER 3. In Search of Influence or Authority? -- tCHAPTER 4. Heard but Not Seen -- tCHAPTER 5. Twenty-Four Hours a Day -- tCHAPTER 6. From Advocates to Adversaries -- tEpilogue: Recurring Themes -- tNotes -- tBibliographic Note -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWho holds ultimate authority for the education of America's children—teachers or parents? Although the relationship between home and school has changed dramatically over the decades, William Cutler's fascinating history argues that it has always been a political one, and his book uncovers for the first time how and why the balance of power has shifted over time. Starting with parental dominance in the mid-nineteenth century, Cutler chronicles how schools' growing bureaucratization and professionalization allowed educators to gain increasing control over the schooling and lives of the children they taught. Central to his story is the role of parent-teacher associations, which helped transform an adversarial relationship into a collaborative one. Yet parents have also been controlled by educators through PTAs, leading to the perception that they are "company unions." Cutler shows how in the 1920s and 1930s schools expanded their responsibility for children's well-being outside the classroom. These efforts sowed the seeds for later conflict as schools came to be held accountable for solving society's problems. Finally, he brings the reader into recent decades, in which a breakdown of trust, racial tension, and "parents' rights" have taken the story full circle, with parents and schools once again at odds. Cutler's book is an invaluable guide to understanding how parent-teacher cooperation, which is essential for our children's educational success, might be achieved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEducationxParent participationxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aEducationxParent participationxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aEducationxParent participationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEducationxParent participationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducational changexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aEducational changexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aEducational changezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEducational changezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHome and schoolxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aHome and schoolxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aHome and schoolzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aHome and schoolzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226307930423Coveruhttps://www.deg